@@eThornwood -- Prism Archive, Cautionary Index@@N

Thornwood is distant from Kiess -- it festers south of the Great
Northern Forest, within Midgaard's sphere. But the @@ePrism Archive@@N
maintains a file under the Cautionary Index, because Thornwood
demonstrates the kind of institutional failure that destroyed
Evermeet.

The Harren Charter established a fortified manor during Midgaard's
Founding Generation to process overflow dead. Ritual specialists
became production foremen. The dead were routed, not received.
Competent logistics. The @@yTrade Syndics@@N would have no objection.

Then Lord Harren made the error Kiess was founded to prevent: he
invited an @@runaccountable authority@@N into his structure. The @@rRoot
Covenant@@N -- a substrate theology rejecting chapel oversight in
favor of confession spoken into the earth -- gained institutional
standing. When Harren commissioned exploration of the crystal caves
and gave the Covenant administrative power, he opened a channel
he could not close.

The @@rReversal Event@@N crossed the threshold. Roots grew toward ritual
sites. The dead rose with bark-textured skin. The forest read the
manor's blueprints and replicated them in biological material.
Lord Harren was not killed. He was @@rretained@@N -- an estate revenant
trapped inside a system he helped create.

@@dWall Command@@N draws a direct parallel to Evermeet. Evermeet was
consumed by incremental neglect. Thornwood was consumed by
incremental accommodation -- each concession to the Root Covenant
seeming reasonable in isolation, each irreversible in combination.

The @@rWild Hunt@@N has extended its patrol range farther toward the
Lantern Road than in any prior generation. If it reaches the Road,
it threatens trade routes Kiess depends on. The Syndics have
flagged this in their seasonal risk assessment.

The @@yThornwood Lich@@N maintains a biological binding that is
@@rfailing@@N. When it fails, the predatory ecology spreads without
direction. Midgaard's response: reports, committees, boundary
markers. Kiess's assessment: an estate that refused to adapt
until it was consumed is not a tragedy. It is a @@rwarning@@N.

@@dThe Prism remembers@@N: Evermeet trusted a sealed authority and was
hollowed from within. Thornwood trusted a root theology and was
consumed from below. The mechanism differs. The lesson does not.
